name: 1h-carbazole, 2,3,4,9-tetrahydro-
Reason: 1H-carbazole has a melting point influenced by its structural components relative to the base melting point of benzene, which is around 5°C. The presence of two phenyl groups contributes to an increase in molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, with an approximate increase of +20°C per group, totaling +40°C. The carbazole ring introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions and potentially hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +30°C. The tetrahydro-functionality introduces additional rigid structures that can participate in dipole interactions and potentially hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +10°C.
